\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Assessing metadata for native access**\\n\\nI’m considering the implications of adding add-opens without metadata. If we do that, getDeclaredField might return NoSuchField, which is problematic. Without the field in metadata, certain lines won't execute in the native environment. There’s a potential to add main metadata related to the Finalizer and Thread classes, but will the checkMetadata accept private JDK fields? Including the Thread field might be too much since we could be overreaching. I need to be cautious about focusing solely on tests.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test resource metadata**\\n\\nI’m wondering if the test resource metadata can register a test helper method. But if the main metadata is missing, the tests should ideally catch that. The library's metadata really should include everything necessary. Existing metadata is based on tests for covered call sites, but if there are active uncovered call sites, then no metadata gets generated. However, once a test covers those areas, the agent might generate the needed metadata. It's a bit of a cycle!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_Byfm3zOtOqGuUruNcoZeaz9r|fc_0ca46a9ec45315950169f55087be08819f81c26e9a3733a92b", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "metadata/com.google.collections/google-collections/1.0/reachability-metadata.json", "edits": [{"oldText": "{\n  \"reflection\" : [\n    {", "newText": "{\n  \"reflection\" : [\n    {\n      \"condition\" : {\n        \"typeReached\" : \"com.google.common.base.internal.Finalizer\"\n      },\n      \"type\" : \"com.google.common.base.FinalizableReference\",\n      \"methods\" : [\n        {\n          \"name\" : \"finalizeReferent\",\n          \"parameterTypes\" : [ ]\n        }\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"condition\" : {\n        \"typeReached\" : \"com.google.common.base.internal.Finalizer\"\n      },\n      \"type\" : \"java.lang.Thread\",\n      \"fields\" : [\n        {\n          \"na